// Temperature is a setting that controls how random or predictable a chat AI's responses are, functioning like a creativity dial that you or the system's designers can adjust.
// At low temperatures (close to 0), the model almost always picks the most likely next word, producing focused, consistent, and deterministic responses—ask it the same question twice and you'll likely get very similar answers.
// At higher temperatures (above 1), the model is more willing to choose less probable words, resulting in more creative, varied, and sometimes surprising outputs, though with a risk of occasionally generating less coherent or relevant text.
// Most chat interfaces use a moderate temperature by default, balancing reliability with natural-sounding variation, though some systems let you adjust this setting when you want more conservative accuracy or more creative exploration.
